@article{Hammar2014,
annote = {2019-01-30

The question behind this Johan Elf's paper is to address whether or not using equilibrium models for gene regulation makes sense. The way they tackle this is by performing single molecule measurements of the time that the lac repressor spends bound to the promoter. To measure this in a single cell they had two types of lac repressor:
1. LacI-Venus fusion that does not respond to IPTG (this in low copy numbers)
2. WT LacI (this in high copy numbers)
The idea of the method was that at time zero the media was changed from saturating IPTG to no IPTG. Before exchanging the media they claim that only the fluorescent LacI-Venus could bind to the operator. Once the media was changed, if the repressor fell off the operator it would most likely be replaced by the other non-fluorescence repressors.
In order to visualize the repressor bound to the operator they performed a 4 s exposure. Only bound immobile repressors would show up in the image as a puncta, while the unbound ones would be blurred away by diffusion. In this way by performing this exposures at different time points, and counting how the fraction of bound repressors decayed over time, they could infer the average residency of the repressor on the operator. They also were able to determine the average time it took for the repressor to bind to the operator.
The paper then goes to discuss that the equilibrium picture doesn't agree with the expected repression measurements. The authors propose different non-equilibrium pictures that could solve the discrepancies, but I honestly didn't like the treatment and carefulness of this part at all. After all the Elf lab is as good as it gets with respect to single molecule in-vivo imaging of transcription factors, but I don't think of them as hardcore theorists carefully thinking about these models.},
