After convincing themselves (and the reader) that the loops do not interfere with the transcription, they go on and test a simple model with Poissonian production of transcripts. As I would have expected, the cell-to-cell variability was significantly higher, therefore they eliminate this option as a viable mechanism for how transcription works. Their data empirically suggested that transcription is a bursty process, having multiple mRNA production events happening consecutively. Their data, such as mean mRNA copy number after induction, fraction of cells without a transcript after induction and the noise, seem to fit a model in which gene expression is a bursty process. As shown in this time trajectory, every time a cell starts producing mRNA, it produces several at the time, and then has long pauses with no transcription. The authors give several suggestive speculations for why mRNA production might be bursty in prokaryotes as well.
This is very much in the spirit of the kind of experiments that we like to do here in the lab. That is why Ido is such a common name we throw as one of the leaders of the field.
