@article{Peterson2015,
abstract = {SignificanceGene expression noise affects a cells biological state and contributes to such phenomena as phenotype switching and cell fate determination. By examining chromosome replication--which is tightly controlled and thus exhibits little noise--we show that variability in mRNA levels across a population is less than previously expected. This noise is due to the transient relaxation of the mRNA from a low- to a high-copy steady state after a gene replication event. Gene location, mRNA degradation rate, and cell doubling time all contribute to observed noise. Our results demonstrate that it is essential to account for gene replication when modelling gene expression or when interpreting experimental results. There are several sources of fluctuations in gene expression. Here we study the effects of time-dependent DNA replication, itself a tightly controlled process, on noise in mRNA levels. Stochastic simulations of constitutive and regulated gene expression are used to analyze the time-averaged mean and variation in each case. The simulations demonstrate that to capture mRNA distributions correctly, chromosome replication must be realistically modeled. Slow relaxation of mRNA from the low copy number steady state before gene replication to the high steady state after replication is set by the transcripts half-life and contributes significantly to the shape of the mRNA distribution. Consequently both the intrinsic kinetics and the gene location play an important role in accounting for the mRNA average and variance. Exact analytic expressions for moments of the mRNA distributions that depend on the DNA copy number, gene location, cell doubling time, and the rates of transcription and degradation are derived for the case of constitutive expression and subsequently extended to provide approximate corrections for regulated expression and RNA polymerase variability. Comparisons of the simulated models and analytical expressions to experimentally measured mRNA distributions show that they better capture the physics of the system than previous theories.},
annote = {This paper sent by Brewster is one of the two papers that followed up his Science paper. In this paper they explore via simulations and analytical work the effect of multiple gene copies during the cell cycle. They claim that the transients are important and once there are two copies of the gene as expected the mRNA copy number relaxes to twice the original amount with a time-scale determined by the mRNA degradation rate.
The paper has some interesting analytical work in which they give some of the rates a random-variable nature rather than a deterministic parameter to include RNAP and transcription factor copy number variability. It would be very interesting to go through these calculations for the Pyramid paper, but for now there are too many details I would like to ignore in my analysis.

2018-05-06
This is the second time I read this paper, this time with different eyes. Now that I am exploring the effect of having multiple gene copies on my own project this study suddenly becomes extremely relevant.
The claim of the paper is pretty simple: noise coming from gene replication is important.
What this means is that depending on the position of the gene along the genome and the growth rate a promoter can have multiple copies. This turns out to affect the overall noise. As shown in Fig. 1 the gene duplicates and then the mRNA has to relax to its new equilibrium value. This relaxation depends on the mRNA degradation rate and it might or might not be accurate to assume the mRNA count reaches steady state. 
For this paper they assume a one-state promoter and claim that they can "fit" to Daniel and Brewster's data just by accounting for this noise source given by the multi-copy case. They work out some analytical expression for the mean and fano-factor and perform some Gillespie simulations to show the improvement that their time-dependent theory gives.
What worries me about this study is the fact that there seem to be endless details to get the "correct theory." It is a little bit overwhelming to think of all the possible unaccountable things for the theory to be right. So when trying to do biophysics and trying to obtain what we claim are meaningful parameters, for these kinetic models it is hard to tells whether or not we are right. Maybe is just a weak point on my faith on the process, but I find right now that what I'm trying to do overly ambitious and maybe meaningless.},
